            </rs> It appeared, that the Prisoner sold the Horse to another Person for 4 s. in whose Possession the same was discovered, and Information of it given to the Prosecutor, who owned the Horse as his: upon which the Prisoner was seized, and confessed the taking of it, which he did not deny upon his trial, but said that as he was going out to work he saw the Horse lying on a green Bank, and took it for one that had been laid aside by the Owners as unserviceable; so thinking he had as good a right to it as any other body, drove him to a Collar-maker to sell for Carrion: He had no other thing to say in his Defence. The Jury brought him in <rs id="t16980608-21-verdict105" type="verdictDescription">
